Week4: Clustering and classification

Clustering and classification

Part 1

Load the packages:

library(MASS)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

Read the data:

data("Boston")

Dataset is quite old, 1978?

Data has:

  • 14 numeric variables
  • 2 of variables are discrete [chas and rad]
  • 12 of variables are continous
  • 506 observations

Overview of the data

Let’s see what is our data made of. Let’s go through the variables

crim
  • per capita crime rate by town
  • right skewed distribution
  • 70 % of observations are below 2
  • last 10% have values that really stand out of the overall distribution
summary(Boston$crim)
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
##  0.00632  0.08204  0.25651  3.61352  3.67708 88.97620
quantile(Boston$crim, probs = seq(0, 1, 0.1))
##        0%       10%       20%       30%       40%       50%       60% 
##  0.006320  0.038195  0.064170  0.099245  0.150380  0.256510  0.550070 
##       70%       80%       90%      100% 
##  1.728440  5.581070 10.753000 88.976200
ggplot(Boston, aes(crim)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth=1,fill="white",colour="black")

zn
  • proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.
  • lots over 25,000 seem to be quite rare because 74 % of areas don’t have those
summary(Boston$zn)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    0.00    0.00    0.00   11.36   12.50  100.00
nrow(Boston[which(Boston$zn == 0),])/nrow(Boston)
## [1] 0.7351779
ggplot(Boston, aes(zn)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth=1,fill="white",colour="black")

indus
  • proportion of non-retail business acres per town.
  • histogram seems little bit polarised. Maby the right tail of histogram represents manufacturing areas?
summary(Boston$indus)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    0.46    5.19    9.69   11.14   18.10   27.74
quantile(Boston$indus, probs = seq(0, 1, 0.1))

ggplot(Boston, aes(indus)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth=1,fill="white",colour="black")

chas
  • Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise).
  • binary variable
  • 94 % of areas don’t bound river
summary(Boston$chas)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
## 0.00000 0.00000 0.00000 0.06917 0.00000 1.00000
prop.table(table(Boston$chas))
## 
##          0          1 
## 0.93083004 0.06916996
Boston %>%
  mutate(bounds = ifelse(chas,'Yes','No')) %>%
  ggplot(., aes(bounds)) +
  geom_bar(fill="white",colour="black")

nox
  • nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million)
  • right skewed distribution with “bumps”
summary(Boston$nox)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.3850  0.4490  0.5380  0.5547  0.6240  0.8710
ggplot(Boston, aes(x=nox)) + 
    geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..),  
                   binwidth=.025,
                   colour="black", fill="white") +
    geom_density(alpha=.2, fill="#FF6666")

rm
  • average number of rooms per dwelling
  • distribution is near normal
summary(Boston$rm)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   3.561   5.886   6.208   6.285   6.623   8.780
ggplot(Boston, aes(x=rm)) + 
    geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..),  
                   binwidth=.25,
                   colour="black", fill="white") +
    geom_density(alpha=.2, fill="#FF6666")

age
  • proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940.
  • left skewed distribution which might due that dataset is quite old
summary(Boston$age)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    2.90   45.02   77.50   68.57   94.08  100.00
ggplot(Boston, aes(x=age)) + 
    geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..),  
                   binwidth=1,
                   colour="black", fill="white") +
    geom_density(alpha=.2, fill="#FF6666") +
    labs(title="Proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940",
        x = "Proportion %", 
        y = "Density")

dis
  • weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centres.
  • right skewed distribution that is most of areas are near employment centre
